.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:3:description: "The runtime engine that consumes the compiled router contract at route time, plus the per-hub serving-authority flip that makes it authoritative. Stage P4b — the literal cutover — built on top of P4a (010-live-activation, which bound each hub's compiled generation as selectedPolicy while serving authority stayed legacy). Three zero-dependency modules: an archetype-adaptive compiled-route engine that reuses each rollout child's proven closed-decision-algebra engine (evaluateCanary or evaluateRoute, by archetype — so the runtime path and the shadow-validated path are the same code), a double-gated fail-safe resolver plus CLI front-door that only serves the compiled route when the runtime flag SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING=1 AND the hub's manifest reads servingAuthority: compiled, and a fenced compare-and-swap flip that moves a hub legacy→compiled behind green gates with a byte-exact rollback. The literal cutover is complete: all seven hubs are flipped legacy→compiled (each with a flag-gated compiled-routing directive in its live SKILL.md and archetype-adaptive re-certification), held inert behind the default-off SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING flag; the frozen benchmark scorer is pinned throughout."
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:6:  - "compiled-route resolver serving flip"
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:27:Three zero-dependency modules do the work. An archetype-adaptive **compiled-route engine** answers `(hubId, taskText)` by loading the hub's compiled policy and reusing the **same** closed-decision-algebra engine the shadow canary already validates — the export name varies by archetype (`evaluateCanary` for the surfaceBundle canary-router, `evaluateRoute` for the plain router), so the runtime path and the shadow-validated path are literally the same code, with no reimplementation to drift. A double-gated **resolver + CLI front-door** returns the compiled decision only when the runtime flag `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING=1` is set (default off) **and** the hub's activation manifest reads `servingAuthority: compiled`; otherwise it returns a legacy sentinel and the caller keeps the prose smart-router. A fenced-CAS **serving flip** moves one hub `legacy → compiled` behind green gates, retaining a byte-identical pre-flip manifest for a byte-exact rollback. The mechanism was proven end-to-end on `sk-code`, then the literal cutover was executed across all seven hubs: each hub's live `SKILL.md` gained a flag-gated compiled-routing directive, was recompiled with archetype-adaptive re-certification, and had serving authority flipped `legacy → compiled`. The cutover is inert by default and reversible two ways, and the frozen benchmark scorer is pinned untouched throughout — so live routing is unchanged until `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING` is enabled (compiled routing is route-gold byte-identical to legacy).
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:38:| **Status** | Complete — the P4b runtime engine (archetype-adaptive compiled-route engine + resolver/CLI front-door + per-hub serving flip) is built, and the literal cutover is executed across all seven hubs: each hub carries a flag-gated compiled-routing directive in its live `SKILL.md`, was recompiled with archetype-adaptive re-certification, and had serving authority flipped `legacy → compiled` (`servingAuthority: compiled` in each `010-live-activation/activation/<hub>/manifest.json`). Each flip is canary-green via the real scorer, route-gold ROUTING byte-identical (only hashes changed), with a byte-exact rollback retained (`manifest.serving-prior.json`). The runtime path is inert by default (`SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING` off), so live routing is unchanged until the flag is enabled. Advisor-hook machine-enforcement remains in progress. Commits: engine `d7da0fca43`, sk-code cutover `2fa3357f80`, remaining-6 cutover `337ca43cfa` (pushed on v4). |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:52:After P4a, each hub's compiled generation is *bound* as `selectedPolicy` but nothing *consumes* it: there is no code that reads the manifest at route time, no gate that decides when the compiled decision is authoritative, and no operated switch to move a hub from legacy to compiled serving. Without a runtime engine the compiled contract is proven-but-dormant; without a fail-safe resolver a live cutover cannot be inert-by-default or reversible; and without a fenced, gated flip the serving change — the single highest-blast step in the whole program — would be an unauditable manual edit to a served pointer. A naive engine would also risk *re-implementing* the routing algebra, forking the runtime path away from the exact code the canary proved green.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:56:Deliver the P4b runtime engine as three small, zero-dependency modules: a pure compiled-route engine that reuses each rollout child's proven canary engine (never a reimplementation), a double-gated fail-safe resolver plus CLI front-door that only serves the compiled route under an explicit runtime flag and a per-hub serving flag, and a fenced compare-and-swap flip that moves a hub `legacy → compiled` behind green gates with a proven byte-exact rollback — then prove the whole path end-to-end on one hub, keep the frozen scorer pinned, and execute the rollout across all seven hubs (wire each live `SKILL.md`, re-certify, and flip serving authority) behind the default-off `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING` flag so live routing is unchanged until it is enabled.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:68:- The **resolver + CLI front-door** `lib/resolve.cjs` — double-gated (`SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING=1` AND manifest `servingAuthority: compiled`), fail-safe (errors → null), with a `--hub/--prompt` CLI that prints the compiled decision or a legacy sentinel.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:75:- Wiring each hub's live `SKILL.md` routing directive to call the resolver - [note] beyond the initial engine build, but now **complete**: each of the seven hubs carries an additive, flag-gated compiled-routing directive that shells to the resolver front-door and self-gates on serving authority (inert while `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING` is off).
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:85:| `011-runtime-engine/lib/resolve.cjs` | Create | Double-gated, fail-safe serving resolver + `--hub/--prompt` CLI front-door |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:89:> The engine and resolver are pure and read-only. Only the flip mutates state, and it does so on the P4a activation manifest under `010-live-activation/activation/<hub>/` (the serving pointer the resolver reads) — never on a live routing file or the scorer. The runtime path stays inert until `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING=1` is set for a hub that has been flipped.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:104:| REQ-003 | The resolver serves the compiled route ONLY when both gates hold, and is otherwise inert. | `resolveRoute(hubId, taskText)` returns null unless `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING=1` AND the hub's `010-live-activation` manifest reads `servingAuthority: compiled`; with the flag off it returns null / the CLI prints a legacy sentinel. |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:105:| REQ-004 | The resolver fails safe: any error resolving the compiled route yields null, never a throw into the routing hot path. | A malformed or missing manifest, or any engine error, returns null (legacy fallback); `servingAuthority()` defaults to `legacy` on a missing/unparseable manifest. |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:124:- **SC-002**: The resolver is inert by default and double-gated — no compiled route is served unless `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING=1` and the hub reads `servingAuthority: compiled`; it fails safe to legacy on any error.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:139:| Dependency | P4a activation manifests (`010-live-activation/activation/<hub>/manifest.json`) | The resolver's serving gate and the flip's CAS both read/write this pointer | Present and P4a-bound; the flip asserts `selectedPolicy` is compiled before flipping |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:158:- **NFR-R02**: The cutover is reversible two independent ways — unset `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING` fleet-wide (the resolver returns null everywhere) or flip a single hub back to `legacy` (per hub).
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:161:- **NFR-A01**: Serving authority is decided solely by the resolver's two gates; the pure engine is never authoritative on its own and never edits a manifest.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:173:- Manifest missing or unparseable: `servingAuthority()` defaults to `legacy`, so the resolver stays inert (fail-safe).
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:177:- Unknown hub id: the engine throws for an unmapped hub, but the resolver's `try/catch` converts that into a null (legacy) at the serving boundary.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:192:| Scope | 13/25 | Three small zero-dependency modules (engine + resolver + flip); reuses the rollout children and the P4a manifest rather than adding a plane |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/spec.md:206:- Should the resolver front-door be invoked in-process by each hub's router or shelled out via the CLI, and what is the latency budget for the compiled path versus the legacy prose router?
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/assets/scripts/README.md:73:| `test_verify_alignment_drift.py` | Unit-style coverage for alignment drift file discovery, language checks, severity behavior, and CLI exit codes. |
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/assets/scripts/README.md:74:| `verify_alignment_drift.py` | Recurring read-only alignment verifier for TypeScript, JavaScript, Python, shell, JSON, and JSONC files. |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:3:description: "Three decisions governing whether and how SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING becomes the repo's effective default: defer global default-on to a staged P4 outcome, single-source compiled eligibility to a valid fresh manifest, and remediate the runtime-to-spec-tree resolver coupling."
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:6:  - "compiled eligibility single source"
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:7:  - "resolver spec-tree coupling remediation"
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:29:      - "Promote the resolver out of the spec tree, or guard it in place? Promote (ADR-003)."
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:75:**How it works**: P0 documents the flag in `ENV-REFERENCE.md` and makes the verify harness distinguish drift-to-legacy from breakage plus a per-hub serving-status readout. P1 adds a drift-detection CI that recomputes each hub's live hash against its minted manifest and fails re-mint-required. P2 canaries default-on in one env profile while the repo default stays off. P3 replaces the two hardcoded allowlists with a data-driven eligibility rule (see ADR-002). P4 flips the repo default hub-by-hub, keeping `=0` as the documented kill-switch. The flip becomes worthwhile precisely when compiled routing does something legacy cannot (a consumed decision, a caught drift), which P0 through P3 create.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:77:**Settlement**: This ruling is settled on the merits of the analysis above (the five premise-failures and the resolver coupling), as the session directive to settle the decision using the fresh-Opus analysis requires. It is a reversible documentation decision: no runtime change follows from it, and the operator may override to flip-now at any time. Acceptance settles the sequencing (phased) only; a separate operator go-ahead gates the start of P0 implementation.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:107:- Four phases of enabling work precede the headline default change. Mitigation: each phase ships standalone value (docs, CI, canary, single-sourced eligibility) rather than being pure overhead.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:129:| 5 | **Open Horizons?** | PASS | Data-driven eligibility (ADR-002) scales to every future skill, so the path does not paint the fleet into a hardcoded corner |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:143:- P2 to P4: a canary env profile, the data-driven eligibility rule (ADR-002), then the staged hub-by-hub default flip.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:153:## ADR-002: Single-source compiled eligibility to a valid fresh manifest
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:168:Which hubs are compiled-eligible is hardcoded in two places: `COMPILED_ROUTING_HUBS` in `advisor-recommend.ts:41` and `HUB_CHILD` in `compiled-route.cjs:23`. Two hand-maintained lists drift apart. A newly created skill is compiled-invisible with no defined way to opt in, and `create-skill` today has zero compiled-routing awareness (a repo grep for compiled-routing tokens under the create-skill mode returns nothing).
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:182:**We chose**: Define compiled eligibility as a single derived predicate: a hub is compiled-eligible if and only if a valid, fresh manifest exists for it (its minted digest matches its live config hash). Both `COMPILED_ROUTING_HUBS` and `HUB_CHILD` derive from that one rule.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:195:| **Data-driven single source (chosen)** | No divergence possible; self-serve onboarding; backward-compat is free by construction | Requires a manifest-freshness read where eligibility is decided | 9/10 |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:209:- The two allowlists cannot diverge because neither is authored by hand.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:231:| 1 | **Necessary?** | PASS | Two hardcoded allowlists exist now and will diverge; new skills have no onboarding path |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:233:| 3 | **Sufficient?** | PASS | One derived predicate covers eligibility, onboarding, and backward-compat together |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:234:| 4 | **Fits Goal?** | PASS | Directly enables a safe global default-on by making eligibility a maintained property, not a code constant |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:247:- P3: a single eligibility predicate keyed on manifest freshness; `COMPILED_ROUTING_HUBS` and `HUB_CHILD` become derived, then removed as hand-authored constants.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:248:- Phase 013: `create-skill` scaffolds the manifest step so onboarding mints eligibility.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:258:## ADR-003: Remediate the runtime-to-spec-tree resolver coupling
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:264:| **Status** | Accepted (P0 remediation; promote the resolver) |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:273:The runtime front door `.opencode/bin/compiled-route.cjs` resolves its resolver from a path inside the spec tree: `compiled-route.cjs:16-21` points at `007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/lib/resolve.cjs`. This repo renumbers and re-nests spec folders constantly (the memory index records repeated hyphen migrations, renumbers, and re-nests). A single such move silently breaks every compiled route to the legacy sentinel, with no observable signal. The repo's own reorganization is a latent drift engine independent of hub-config edits.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:277:- The shim must keep failing safe to legacy on any resolver error (that property is correct and stays).
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:278:- Any promotion must not duplicate the resolver logic; it stays single-sourced.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:287:**We chose**: Promote the resolver to a stable runtime location beside the shim (recommended), rather than leave it in the spec tree behind a path guard.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:289:**How it works**: `resolve.cjs` moves to a durable runtime path (for example `.opencode/bin/lib/`), and the shim requires it from there. The spec-tree copy becomes the authored source that is built or copied into the runtime location, so a spec renumber no longer moves the file the runtime depends on.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:300:| **Promote resolver to a runtime path (chosen)** | Removes the drift source rather than guarding it; runtime no longer depends on spec-tree layout | A small build or copy step to keep the runtime copy current | 8/10 |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:304:**Why this one**: Guarding a fragile path detects the break; promoting the file removes the break. Removing a latent failure mode beats instrumenting it.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:315:- The runtime dependency graph stops reaching into the spec tree.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:318:- A build or copy step keeps the runtime resolver current. Mitigation: wire it into the same mint/backfill flow that maintains manifests.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:324:| Runtime copy goes stale vs authored source | M | Add a freshness check to the drift-CI (P1) so a stale runtime resolver fails the same gate as a stale manifest |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:338:| 4 | **Fits Goal?** | PASS | A default-on fleet cannot rest on a resolver that a spec move can sever |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:339:| 5 | **Open Horizons?** | PASS | A stable runtime path is the correct long-term home regardless of spec-tree churn |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:352:- P1: the drift-CI also checks the runtime resolver is current with its authored source.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:354:**How to roll back**: Restore the shim's original require path to the spec-tree resolver; the file still exists there, and the shim already fails safe, so the revert is a one-line change with no behavior risk.
