   152	<!-- ANCHOR:adr-002 -->
   153	## ADR-002: Single-source compiled eligibility to a valid fresh manifest
   154	
   155	### Metadata
   156	
   157	| Field | Value |
   158	|-------|-------|
   159	| **Status** | Accepted (design direction; implemented in P3) |
   160	| **Date** | 2026-07-20 |
   161	| **Deciders** | Operator, Claude Opus 4.8 |
   162	
   163	---
   164	
   165	<!-- ANCHOR:adr-002-context -->
   166	### Context
   167	
   168	Which hubs are compiled-eligible is hardcoded in two places: `COMPILED_ROUTING_HUBS` in `advisor-recommend.ts:41` and `HUB_CHILD` in `compiled-route.cjs:23`. Two hand-maintained lists drift apart. A newly created skill is compiled-invisible with no defined way to opt in, and `create-skill` today has zero compiled-routing awareness (a repo grep for compiled-routing tokens under the create-skill mode returns nothing).
   169	
   170	### Constraints
   171	
   172	- Backward-compat is required: a skill lacking the compiled JSONs or snapshot must route via legacy with no behavior change.
   173	- Onboarding must be explicit and self-serve, not a code edit in two files.
   174	
   175	<!-- /ANCHOR:adr-002-context -->
   176	
   177	---
   178	
   179	<!-- ANCHOR:adr-002-decision -->
   180	### Decision
   181	
   182	**We chose**: Define compiled eligibility as a single derived predicate: a hub is compiled-eligible if and only if a valid, fresh manifest exists for it (its minted digest matches its live config hash). Both `COMPILED_ROUTING_HUBS` and `HUB_CHILD` derive from that one rule.
   183	
   184	**How it works**: Onboarding a skill means minting its manifest; backward-compat means the absence of a manifest yields legacy by construction. `create-skill` (phase 013) mints or scaffolds the manifest step so new hubs are born either compiled-ready or explicitly legacy, never silently half-wired.
   185	
   186	<!-- /ANCHOR:adr-002-decision -->
   187	
   188	---
   189	
   190	<!-- ANCHOR:adr-002-alternatives -->
   191	### Alternatives Considered
   192	
   193	| Option | Pros | Cons | Score |
   194	|--------|------|------|-------|
   195	| **Data-driven single source (chosen)** | No divergence possible; self-serve onboarding; backward-compat is free by construction | Requires a manifest-freshness read where eligibility is decided | 9/10 |
   196	| One hardcoded list imported by both | Removes duplication cheaply | Still manual; a new skill still needs a code edit to onboard | 6/10 |
   197	| Keep two lists, reconcile by hand | No new code | The exact divergence risk this ADR exists to remove | 3/10 |
   198	
   199	**Why this one**: Eligibility should be a property of the artifacts (does a fresh manifest exist), not a fact duplicated in code. That makes onboarding and backward-compat the same mechanism viewed from two sides.
   200	
   201	<!-- /ANCHOR:adr-002-alternatives -->
   202	
   203	---
   204	
   205	<!-- ANCHOR:adr-002-consequences -->
   206	### Consequences
   207	
   208	**What improves**:
   209	- The two allowlists cannot diverge because neither is authored by hand.
   210	- A new or edited skill has one clear compiled state derived from whether its manifest is fresh.
   211	
   212	**What it costs**:
   213	- Eligibility now reads manifest freshness on the decision path. Mitigation: the freshness check is a hash comparison already computed by the serve-time shim, so it is reused, not added.
   214	
   215	**Risks**:
   216	
   217	| Risk | Impact | Mitigation |
   218	|------|--------|------------|
   219	| Freshness read on the hot path adds latency | L | Reuse the shim's existing hash recompute; cache per process |
   220	| Migration removes the hardcoded sets prematurely | M | Keep the sets as a pinned fallback until P3 parity is proven, then delete in one change |
   221	
   222	<!-- /ANCHOR:adr-002-consequences -->
   223	
   224	---
   225	
   226	<!-- ANCHOR:adr-002-five-checks -->
   227	### Five Checks Evaluation
   228	
   229	| # | Check | Result | Evidence |
   230	|---|-------|--------|----------|
   231	| 1 | **Necessary?** | PASS | Two hardcoded allowlists exist now and will diverge; new skills have no onboarding path |
   232	| 2 | **Beyond Local Maxima?** | PASS | The cheaper import-one-list option is weighed and rejected for still being manual |
   233	| 3 | **Sufficient?** | PASS | One derived predicate covers eligibility, onboarding, and backward-compat together |
   234	| 4 | **Fits Goal?** | PASS | Directly enables a safe global default-on by making eligibility a maintained property, not a code constant |
   235	| 5 | **Open Horizons?** | PASS | Scales to any number of future skills with no code edit per skill |
   236	
   237	**Checks Summary**: 5/5 PASS
   238	
   239	<!-- /ANCHOR:adr-002-five-checks -->
   240	
   241	---
   242	
   243	<!-- ANCHOR:adr-002-impl -->
   244	### Implementation
   245	
   246	**What changes**:
   247	- P3: a single eligibility predicate keyed on manifest freshness; `COMPILED_ROUTING_HUBS` and `HUB_CHILD` become derived, then removed as hand-authored constants.
   248	- Phase 013: `create-skill` scaffolds the manifest step so onboarding mints eligibility.
   249	
   250	**How to roll back**: Retain the hardcoded sets as a pinned fallback through P3; if the derived predicate misbehaves, restore the constants (a one-file revert in each of the two locations).
   251	
   252	<!-- /ANCHOR:adr-002-impl -->
   253	<!-- /ANCHOR:adr-002 -->
   254	
   255	---
   256	
   257	<!-- ANCHOR:adr-003 -->
   258	## ADR-003: Remediate the runtime-to-spec-tree resolver coupling
   259	
   260	### Metadata
   261	
   262	| Field | Value |
   263	|-------|-------|
   264	| **Status** | Accepted (P0 remediation; promote the resolver) |
   265	| **Date** | 2026-07-20 |
   266	| **Deciders** | Operator, Claude Opus 4.8 |
   267	
   268	---
   269	
   270	<!-- ANCHOR:adr-003-context -->
   271	### Context
   272	
   273	The runtime front door `.opencode/bin/compiled-route.cjs` resolves its resolver from a path inside the spec tree: `compiled-route.cjs:16-21` points at `007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/lib/resolve.cjs`. This repo renumbers and re-nests spec folders constantly (the memory index records repeated hyphen migrations, renumbers, and re-nests). A single such move silently breaks every compiled route to the legacy sentinel, with no observable signal. The repo's own reorganization is a latent drift engine independent of hub-config edits.
   274	
   275	### Constraints
   276	
   277	- The shim must keep failing safe to legacy on any resolver error (that property is correct and stays).
   278	- Any promotion must not duplicate the resolver logic; it stays single-sourced.
   279	
   280	<!-- /ANCHOR:adr-003-context -->
   281	
   282	---
   283	
   284	<!-- ANCHOR:adr-003-decision -->
   285	### Decision
   286	
   287	**We chose**: Promote the resolver to a stable runtime location beside the shim (recommended), rather than leave it in the spec tree behind a path guard.
   288	
   289	**How it works**: `resolve.cjs` moves to a durable runtime path (for example `.opencode/bin/lib/`), and the shim requires it from there. The spec-tree copy becomes the authored source that is built or copied into the runtime location, so a spec renumber no longer moves the file the runtime depends on.
   290	
   291	<!-- /ANCHOR:adr-003-decision -->
   292	
   293	---
   294	
   295	<!-- ANCHOR:adr-003-alternatives -->
   296	### Alternatives Considered
   297	
   298	| Option | Pros | Cons | Score |
   299	|--------|------|------|-------|
   300	| **Promote resolver to a runtime path (chosen)** | Removes the drift source rather than guarding it; runtime no longer depends on spec-tree layout | A small build or copy step to keep the runtime copy current | 8/10 |
   301	| Path-integrity guard in place | Cheapest; fails loudly on a broken path | Keeps the coupling; converts silent breakage to loud breakage but still breaks on every renumber | 6/10 |
   302	| Leave as-is and document | No work now | The drift source remains and stays silent; documentation does not stop a renumber | 4/10 |
   303	
   304	**Why this one**: Guarding a fragile path detects the break; promoting the file removes the break. Removing a latent failure mode beats instrumenting it.
   305	
   306	<!-- /ANCHOR:adr-003-alternatives -->
   307	
   308	---
   309	
   310	<!-- ANCHOR:adr-003-consequences -->
   311	### Consequences
   312	
   313	**What improves**:
   314	- A spec renumber or re-nest can no longer sever compiled routing.
   315	- The runtime dependency graph stops reaching into the spec tree.
   316	
   317	**What it costs**:
   318	- A build or copy step keeps the runtime resolver current. Mitigation: wire it into the same mint/backfill flow that maintains manifests.
   319	
   320	**Risks**:
   321	
   322	| Risk | Impact | Mitigation |
   323	|------|--------|------------|
   324	| Runtime copy goes stale vs authored source | M | Add a freshness check to the drift-CI (P1) so a stale runtime resolver fails the same gate as a stale manifest |
   325	
   326	<!-- /ANCHOR:adr-003-consequences -->
   327	
   328	---
   329	
   330	<!-- ANCHOR:adr-003-five-checks -->
   120	      v enabled
   121	compiled decision ---- parity gate ----> served only when legacy-equivalent
   122	```
   123	<!-- /ANCHOR:architecture -->
   124	
